Ansar-ud-Deen Society of Nigeria (ADSN), Lagos State Council has held an induction seminar for the newly-elected branch officers. ADSN Lagos State Council Chairman, Alhaji Alhaji AbdulRahman Olabode Salaudeen said the programme would equip the officers with adequate knowledge on how to pilot the affairs of the association which will lead to increased productivity. “I can attest to the success of the programme over the years and the positive impact to the society, it has allowed our members to understand what the society stands for and the seminar has equipped them with the structural and governmental policies of the society,” he said. According to him, the society has imbibed innovative opportunities that would create an enabling environment for investment.   30 schools for sports fiesta     Graft: Group urges council leader to clear his name     Obtain your PVC, Nigerians told   “We want to be more innovative, particularly we want to create an enabling environment for investment. The issues of seeking donations, begging people for money, we want to put an end to it. We are going to educate our members on how to invest wisely to raise their living standard and also provide funding to the organisation. By doing this, we will create more businesses so that members will be resourceful in terms of wealth creation. Likewise our youths will be encouraged to prioritise innovation instead of waiting for governments to provide jobs for them,” Alhaji Salaudeen. ADSN National Secretary Alhaji Iskeel Ola Yusuf, assured that the officers have been well-trained and acquainted with the goal of the organisation. “I can assure you, there is no officer in any of the branches in Lagos that will ask questions about the affairs of the society that will not be able to give the correct answer,” he said. ADSN Lagos State Council Chairperson, Alhaja Shakirat Animashaun, said the training will go a long way to address some of the challenges bedevilling the society.